{"id":"2005.07846","submitter":"Gilyoung Cheong","authors":"Gilyoung Cheong, Jungin Lee, Hayan Nam, and Myungjun Yu","title":"Jordan--Landau theorem for matrices over finite fields","comments":"19 pages. A conjecture in the previous draft has been resolved and\n  its proof is included, and another author has been added","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given a positive integer $r$ and a prime power $q$, we estimate the\nprobability that the characteristic polynomial $f_{A}(t)$ of a random matrix\n$A$ in $\\mathrm{GL}_{n}(\\mathbb{F}_{q})$ is square-free with $r$ (monic)\nirreducible factors when $n$ is large. We also estimate the analogous\nprobability that $f_{A}(t)$ has $r$ irreducible factors counting with\nmultiplicity. In either case, the main term $(\\log n)^{r-1}((r-1)!n)^{-1}$ and\nthe error term $O((\\log n)^{r-2}n^{-1})$, whose implied constant only depends\non $r$ but not on $q$ nor $n$, coincide with the probability that a random\npermutation on $n$ letters is a product of $r$ disjoint cycles. The main\ningredient of our proof is a recursion argument due to S. D. Cohen, which was\npreviously used to estimate the probability that a random degree $n$ monic\npolynomial in $\\mathbb{F}_{q}[t]$ is square-free with $r$ irreducible factors\nand the analogous probability that the polynomial has $r$ irreducible factors\ncounting with multiplicity. We obtain our result by carefully modifying Cohen's\nrecursion argument in the matrix setting, using Reiner's theorem that counts\nthe number of $n \\times n$ matrices with a fixed characteristic polynomial over\n$\\mathbb{F}_{q}$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 16 May 2020 02:19:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 28 Jul 2022 08:03:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 8 Sep 2022 07:48:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-09"}
